Q: What does “random access” mean?
    Random access means you can directly go to any position.
arr = [10, 20, 30, 40]
arr[2] → 30   ✅ (direct access) - This is fast because the index is known.

How a Linked List works: A linked list is made of nodes.
Each node contains:
Data and Address of the next node

10 → 20 → 30 → 40 → null
You only know the first node (head).

Suppose you want the 3rd element (30).
In an array: You directly jump to index 2
In a linked list: You must start from the head
Move node by node
Step-by-step access:
Start at 10
Move to 20
Move to 30 ✅
You cannot jump directly to 30.
👉 You must traverse sequentially

Node current = head;   // start from first node
int position = 3;
for (int i = 1; i < position; i++) {
    current = current.next;
}
System.out.println(current.data); // prints 30

Q: Why insertion is efficient? : Because only links change, not memory shifting

Q: Why linked list is slower than array? Because of cache miss + traversal

Q: What is Linked List: A Linked List is a linear data structure where elements are not stored in continuous memory.
Each element is called a node. and Every node has data and reference(link) to the next node

Q: What is Node in LL: A Node is the basic building block of a linked list.
A linked list is made by connecting many nodes together.

Q: What is Head in LL: Head is the reference to the first node of the linked list.
                    It is used to start accessing the list.

Q: What is Tail in LL: Tail is the reference to the last node of the linked list.
                    The next of tail is always null (in singly linked list).


Why Linked List? (Why not just arrays?)
| Problem          | Explanation                   |
| ---------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Fixed size       | Size must be known in advance |
| Insertion costly | Shifting elements needed      |
| Deletion costly  | Shifting again                |
| Memory waste     | Extra unused slots            |


Advantages of Linked List ✅
| Advantage      | Why                  |
| -------------- | -------------------- |
| Dynamic size   | Grows/shrinks easily |
| Easy insertion | No shifting          |
| Easy deletion  | Just change links    |

Disadvantages ❌
| Disadvantage     | Why                 |
| ---------------- | ------------------- |
| No random access | Cannot do `list[5]` |
| Extra memory     | For storing links   |
| Slower access    | Traversal needed    |

Types of LinkedList:

1. Singly Linked List
Data | Next → Data | Next → Data | Next → null

2. Doubly Linked List
null ← Prev | Data | Next → Prev | Data | Next → null

3. Circular Linked List
Last node points back to first node

